<br>
----------<br>
<br>
I know you receive countless e-mails every day, so I appreciate the fact that you're taking the time to review this one.  I also realize that the patch 1.62 on Pendragon is not yet complete.  Consequently, I very much hope that my comments on it are both premature and in the end unjustified.  Patch 1.39 is the first patch I can identify which specifically identified Blademasters and Mercenaries as troubled classes.  From the bottom of my heart, I sincerely wish that 1.62 could be the last one to do so.  So, if there are further changes to the Blademaster and the Celtic Dual line planned in 1.62 please disregard my comments.  But, if there are not, please continue reading.<br>
<br>
In an effort to keep this as brief as possible, these are my concerns:<br>
<br>
1) From the patch notes: &quot;a Blademaster and a Hero working together should be much more effective in dealing damage than two Heroes working together.&quot;  As the notes later acknowledge, this has never been the case.  However, these changes are simply not sufficient to change that.  Testing has shown that the changes on Pendragon to the side positional changes for Celtic Dual make them only marginally better than those in the Blades/Blunt/Pierce side positional weapon styles.  In order for this justification to work, the light tank damage will need to be made dramatically better than it currently is. <br>
<br>
2) The basic concept proposed in the 1.62B notes is essentially flawed.  The previously stated tank concept was that light tanks could deal more damage, but that heavy tanks could take more.  At an intuitive level, this should balance out perfectly so that an “even” fight between a heavy tank and a light tank should come down to the wire.  If, as the 1.62B notes state, this is no longer the objective, then light tanks are inherently inferior to heavy tanks. <br>
<br>
3) Bleed damage is not a solution as implemented.  Bleed damage went from doing 5 damage over 2-3 rounds of combat to doing 25 damage over 2-3 rounds of combat.  Yes, this is a marked increase.  However, when even casters have 850 health, this is a negligible change.  Further, bleed damage appears to have been increased for all styles, not just Celtic Dual or Dual Wield styles.<br>
<br>
4) The Style Chains that were improved are ones that are among the most difficult to use in realm versus realm combat.  <br>
<br>
5) All of the Celtic Dual styles range from inferior to marginally better than the base line styles in Hibernia.  Yet a Blademaster spends 1274 specialization points to max out this skill.  While the off hand damage as opposed to a non dual wielder is nice, the differences in styles absolutely fail to justify this expenditure of points.  Especially when compared to the single specialization lines of Large Weapon and Celtic Spear.  (I’m sure you’re aware of it, but if not please consider the data presented at <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://home.nc.rr.com/obsidianguard/wyrd/Hibernia.htm">home.nc.rr.com/obsidiangu...bernia.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )  There is simply no logical reason for this to be the case.<br>
<br>
I’m hardly going to make any ridiculous comments about quitting the game over these changes.  Aside from the fact that such claims would be a lie, I’m very excited about the changes to both the Valewalker and the Eldritch that were also in this patch.  However, as things stand, I find myself very disappointed with the Blademaster changes.  I’m a stubborn person.  (I believe a psychological profile of Blademaster and Mercenary players would show that most of us are.)  I’ll continue to play my Blademaster for some time, no matter how frustrating I find it.  However, I very strongly believe that this patch is not a true solution.<br>
<br>
Thank you again for your time and attention to this matter.<br>
<br>
John Dunn aka Oog Smash RR4, Lvl 50 Blademaster, LGM Weaponcrafter Kay Server<br>
